    <item>
      <title>Smartphones and Augmenting Humanity</title>
      <link>https://ashfurrow.com/blog/smartphones-and-augmenting-humanity/</link>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;A few weeks ago, shortly after Pokemon Go launched, I saw a pretty messed up image get circulated &amp;lsquo;round the internet, with comments to the effect of &amp;ldquo;haha, this is &lt;em&gt;so&lt;/em&gt; edgy!&amp;rdquo; But it made me pretty angry.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://pawelkuczynski.com"&gt;&lt;img src="https://ashfurrow.com/img/blog/smartphones-and-augmenting-humanity/pikachu.jpg" alt="Bad satire" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Ohhhhhhh my goshhhhhh&lt;/em&gt; the pretension practically oozes off my screen. Pokemon Go became popular and despite benefits like spending more time outside, the game&amp;rsquo;s popularity demanded snarky responses. Thinkpieces had to be written! Snarky comics had to be published! Ugh.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://wumo.com/wumo/2016/08/11"&gt;&lt;img src="https://ashfurrow.com/img/blog/smartphones-and-augmenting-humanity/cliff.png" alt="Worse satire" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;m so tired of this. Pokemon Go entertains people, gets them outside, helps them make new friends, all kinds of awesome things. But it&amp;rsquo;s an app, which is technology, and technology is bad, right? So we get this faux intellectual backlash coming from people who you&amp;rsquo;d think would know better: so called &amp;ldquo;satirists.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The reason this has me so frustrated is something I read back in January:&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&lt;blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-conversation="none" data-lang="en"&gt;&lt;p lang="en" dir="ltr"&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s not actually edgy to call folk with smart phones drones, it IS actually edgy to admit that some ppl need them to communicate w world&lt;/p&gt;&amp;mdash; Sook Moon (@doloresonthedot) &lt;a href="https://twitter.com/doloresonthedot/status/701369715621502980"&gt;February 21, 2016&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt; &lt;script async src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;The internet ‚Äì and technology in general ‚Äì is at its best when it helps people lead fulfilling lives. By many measures, smartphones do that. All the thinkpieces criticizing people for using smartphones, all the comics mocking people for using apps, they&amp;rsquo;re all intellectually lazy, designed to satisfy one group of people by othering another. And we all act like it&amp;rsquo;s normal to mock people for relying on technology.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Everyone acts like it&amp;rsquo;s acceptable to hate on people who rely on the internet, but it&amp;rsquo;s not. This is just a thing that society does in order to shame people who find communicating online easier than in person. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s got to stop.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Smartphones augment human intelligence, the internet enables new kinds of friendships, and technology provides new avenues of creativity. Computers are &lt;a href="https://www.brainpickings.org/2011/12/21/steve-jobs-bicycle-for-the-mind-1990/"&gt;bicycles for our minds&lt;/a&gt; and we take them for granted. As a society, we&amp;rsquo;ve accepted the idea that relying on technology is a form of weakness. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;No more edgy comics. No more faux-provocative thinkpieces. They&amp;rsquo;re all wrong. If we fail to challenge their message, then we are complicit in the harm they do.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
      <pubDate>Thu, 18 Aug 2016 20:18:47 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://ashfurrow.com/blog/smartphones-and-augmenting-humanity/</guid>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Photography Retrospective</title>
      <link>https://ashfurrow.com/blog/photography-retrospective/</link>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;In February of 2012, I wrote that &lt;a href="https://ashfurrow.com/blog/effort-to-improved-skill-ratio-and-expertise/"&gt;I would not be buying a camera&lt;/a&gt;. Two months later, &lt;a href="https://ashfurrow.com/blog/so-i-bought-a-camera/"&gt;I did buy one&lt;/a&gt;, and that decision has come to shape a lot of who I am today. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&amp;rsquo;s funny how four years seems like a long time, but also feels really short, too. Photography exploded into my life, taking up all my spare time, attention, and money. I knew it would when I started. After all, I&amp;rsquo;ve always loved gadgets and gizmos, and photography is rife with things to fiddle with and obsess over.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I kept buying nicer and nicer lenses, and nicer and nicer cameras, until I had &amp;ldquo;the setup&amp;rdquo;, what I thought would signal to other photographers (and myself) that I was serious about photography. It was never enough. I had a problem. I felt addicted to buying gear. I would feel crummy and think that buying such-and-such new photography thing would make me feel better, and it did, but that elation would quickly subside when I realized that I &lt;em&gt;shouldn&amp;rsquo;t have bought that&lt;/em&gt;. So that would make me feel crummy too and the cycle would repeat. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Buying photography gear was an unhealthy coping mechanism that I used to deal with my &lt;a href="https://ashfurrow.com/blog/depression/"&gt;depression&lt;/a&gt;, but eventually I did manage to stop before I did unrepairable damage to my marriage and finances. When I moved to New York, I got the help I needed, and that&amp;rsquo;s made recovery from &amp;ldquo;gear acquisition syndrome&amp;rdquo; possible.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That&amp;rsquo;s the dark side of my photography. But there&amp;rsquo;s a good side, too: photography is a huge, positive part of my life ‚Äì in both lofty and day-to-day senses. Let me explain both.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I wanted &lt;em&gt;so much&lt;/em&gt; to feel like a &amp;ldquo;real photographer&amp;rdquo;, and I bought gear that I thought would help. That wasn&amp;rsquo;t smart, but it did lead to making making a lot of photos, and that &lt;em&gt;did&lt;/em&gt; help me feel like a photographer. More than that, I eventually stopped caring about how I appear to others as a photographer; photography has become something I do &lt;em&gt;for me&lt;/em&gt;. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Buying gear didn&amp;rsquo;t help, but actually using the gear I had &lt;em&gt;did&lt;/em&gt;. And eventually, I learnt that it didn&amp;rsquo;t really matter anyway.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Today, a camera accompanies me everywhere I go. Every time I leave my apartment, I have my camera in my bag, and the camera is already in my hand by the time my feet hit the sidewalk.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&lt;blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-lang="en"&gt;&lt;p lang="en" dir="ltr"&gt;Walk to work: 30 minutes of Spotify. &lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Walk to work, carrying a camera: 45 minutes of ‚Äúwow, everything is amazing!‚Äù ‚Ä¶ and Spotify.&lt;/p&gt;&amp;mdash; Ash Furrow (@ashfurrow) &lt;a href="https://twitter.com/ashfurrow/status/695643794922934272"&gt;February 5, 2016&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt; &lt;script async src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;Photography taught me to &lt;a href="https://ashfurrow.com/blog/developers-should-learn-photography/"&gt;learn from my mistakes&lt;/a&gt;; if a photo didn&amp;rsquo;t turn out the way I wanted, I figured out why. Once I found out what went wrong, I tried not to do it again.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A lot of the choices I&amp;rsquo;ve made haven&amp;rsquo;t turned out for the best, but I&amp;rsquo;m learning from them.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This summer has actually been the first time in my life that I haven&amp;rsquo;t lived paycheque-to-paycheque. It sucks that it took until my late twenties to get my shit together, but I want to concentrate on the fact that &lt;em&gt;I&amp;rsquo;m actually getting my shit together&lt;/em&gt;. And honestly, photography only exacerbated an obsession with buying things. But, it did help in unique ways that I think only art could have. It taught me lessons I&amp;rsquo;ve applied to other parts of my life, and it now helps take my mind off things when I do feel down. It&amp;rsquo;s become a healthy coping mechanism.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If I could go back and explain all this to myself in 2012, when I was buying my first camera, I&amp;rsquo;m not sure my younger self would understand. It&amp;rsquo;s like &lt;a href="https://byorgey.wordpress.com/2009/01/12/abstraction-intuition-and-the-monad-tutorial-fallacy/"&gt;monads&lt;/a&gt;, you can&amp;rsquo;t explain how they work because that comprehension can only come from struggling with them. You can&amp;rsquo;t take a shortcut. With buying photography gear, I didn&amp;rsquo;t understand how I was hurting myself until I had struggled for a while. Maybe the struggle was necessary. In any case, I&amp;rsquo;m glad it&amp;rsquo;s ending.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So that&amp;rsquo;s my retrospective on photography, at least so far: a hobby-turned-obsession that cost a lot of money and caused a lot of stress, but also a hobby that became a healthy coping mechanism with a lot of fun. Like most everything, photography hasn&amp;rsquo;t been &amp;ldquo;good&amp;rdquo; or &amp;ldquo;bad&amp;rdquo;, but a bit of both. I can live with that.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
      <pubDate>Wed, 17 Aug 2016 00:21:15 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://ashfurrow.com/blog/photography-retrospective/</guid>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Fresh macOS Setup</title>
      <link>https://ashfurrow.com/blog/fresh-macos-setup/</link>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;There are a bunch of things I do when I re-install macOS on a computer, or when I begin working on a new computer. I don&amp;rsquo;t do this often, so it&amp;rsquo;s easy to forget the steps. So I &lt;a href="https://gist.github.com/ashfurrow/3865eed417a5fbe8402708e2c706eea6"&gt;documented everything in a gist&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I used to keep these steps in Notes.app but figured they should be public anyway (open source by default, right?) so here we are.&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;script src="https://gist.github.com/ashfurrow/3865eed417a5fbe8402708e2c706eea6.js"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;



&lt;p&gt;One thing I&amp;rsquo;ve added recently, that&amp;rsquo;s super-important to me, is to untrust a certain certificate. Blue Coat is a company that creates &lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blue_Coat_Systems#Controversy"&gt;internet surveillance and censorship software&lt;/a&gt; and Semantic gave them an intermediate CA certificate. That means they can sign arbitrary certificates that you&amp;rsquo;re computer will trust (because your computer trusts Semantic, and Semantic trusts Blue Coat). &lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;&lt;blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-lang="en"&gt;&lt;p lang="en" dir="ltr"&gt;BlueCoat now has a CA signed by Symantec &lt;a href="https://t.co/8OXmtpT6eX"&gt;https://t.co/8OXmtpT6eX&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Here&amp;rsquo;s how to untrust it &lt;a href="https://t.co/NDlbqKqqld"&gt;https://t.co/NDlbqKqqld&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="https://t.co/mBD68nrVsD"&gt;pic.twitter.com/mBD68nrVsD&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&amp;mdash; Filippo Valsorda (@FiloSottile) &lt;a href="https://twitter.com/FiloSottile/status/735940720931012608"&gt;May 26, 2016&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt; &lt;script async src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8"&gt;&lt;/script&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;m not really into the idea of my computer trusting a company like Blue Coat, so I &lt;a href="https://blog.filippo.io/untrusting-an-intermediate-ca-on-os-x/"&gt;follow the instructions&lt;/a&gt; to untrust this certificate. I highly recommend you do, too.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And I recommend you document everything you do to make your computer awesome! &lt;/p&gt;
</description>
      <pubDate>Tue, 09 Aug 2016 14:24:52 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://ashfurrow.com/blog/fresh-macos-setup/</guid>
